        "content": "<p>This has come up before, but this time it's pretty horrible, at least I think it is.</p>\n<p>Take a look at the docs for <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib_docs/analysis/complex/polynomial.html#complex.exists_root\" title=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib_docs/analysis/complex/polynomial.html#complex.exists_root\"><code>complex.exists_root</code></a>, the Lean proof of the fundamental theorem of algebra. Read the statement of the theorem. You see what it says about all polynomials having a root? What about the polynomial <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>37</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f(z)=37</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.04398em;\">z</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">3</span><span class=\"mord\">7</span></span></span></span>? It has degree 0 and no root.</p>\n<p>Exercise: what is going on?</p>",
        "id": 197055508,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1589117303
    },
    {
